mitre_attack_techniques.signature_description: Adversaries may communicate using application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic.
Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol.
Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit.
Adversaries may perform software packing or virtual machine software protection to conceal their code.
May sleep (evasive loops) to hinder dynamic analysis
Creates a DirectInput object (often for capturing keystrokes)
Monitors certain registry keys / values for changes (often done to protect autostart functionality)
May try to detect the virtual machine to hinder analysis (VM artifact strings found in memory)
Uses HTTPS for network communication, use the SSL MITM Proxy cookbook for further analysis
Uses a known web browser user agent for HTTP communication

signature_matches.name: packed with generic packer
signature_matches.description: anti-analysis/packer/generic
match_data: mnemonic: pushad
mnemonic: popad
cross section flow
signature_matches.rule_src:
rule:
  meta:
    name: packed with generic packer
    namespace: anti-analysis/packer/generic
    authors:
      - william.ballenthin@mandiant.com
    scopes:
      static: function
      dynamic: unsupported
    att&ck:
      - Defense Evasion::Obfuscated Files or Information::Software Packing [T1027.002]
    mbc:
      - Anti-Static Analysis::Software Packing::Standard Compression [F0001.002]
    examples:
      - Practical Malware Analysis Lab 18-01.exe_:0x409dc0
  features:
    - and:
      - or:
        - mnemonic: pusha
        - mnemonic: pushad  # vivisect
      - or:
        - mnemonic: popa
        - mnemonic: popad  # vivisect
      - characteristic: cross section flow
      - not:
        - match: contain pusha popa sequence

signature_matches.name: packed with UPX
signature_matches.description: anti-analysis/packer/upx
match_data: section: UPX1
section: UPX0
signature_matches.rule_src:
rule:
  meta:
    name: packed with UPX
    namespace: anti-analysis/packer/upx
    authors:
      - william.ballenthin@mandiant.com
    scopes:
      static: file
      dynamic: file
    att&ck:
      - Defense Evasion::Obfuscated Files or Information::Software Packing [T1027.002]
    mbc:
      - Anti-Static Analysis::Software Packing::UPX [F0001.008]
    examples:
      - CD2CBA9E6313E8DF2C1273593E649682
      - Practical Malware Analysis Lab 01-02.exe_:0x0401000
  features:
    - or:
      - and:
        - format: pe
        - or:
          - section: UPX0
          - section: UPX1
      - and:
        - format: elf
        - or:
          - string: "UPX!"

signature_matches.name: dead_connect
signature_matches.description: Attempts to connect to a dead IP:Port (2 unique times)

signature_matches.description: At least one IP Address, Domain, or File Name was found in a crypto call

T1027.002.description: Adversaries may perform software packing or virtual machine software protection to conceal their code.

T1071.description: Adversaries may communicate using application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic.
Uses a known web browser user agent for HTTP communication

T1573.description: Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol.
Uses HTTPS for network communication, use the SSL MITM Proxy cookbook for further analysis

T1027.description: Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit.

T1497.description: May sleep (evasive loops) to hinder dynamic analysis

T1056.description: Creates a DirectInput object (often for capturing keystrokes)

T1012.description: Monitors certain registry keys / values for changes (often done to protect autostart functionality)

T1518.001.description: May try to detect the virtual machine to hinder analysis (VM artifact strings found in memory)
